{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_016JrCvMvPaGtY2cyDrrBRMC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012pi96cviNGVHAgCHbNzj59","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Files placed inside subdirectories of the watched root are processed, not only root-level files","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A real failure occurs when the watcher is initialized without recursive:true (or equivalent), causing the OS to silently ignore subdirectory events. A Unit test that mocks fs.watch can verify that recursive:true is passed as an argument, but only Integration testing with a real filesystem directory structure and actual file writes catches the subtle failure: does the watcher *actually* observe subdirectories when properly configured? This requires watching real subdirectories and verifying events propagate through the full pipeline.","test_description":"Create a temporary directory structure with subdirectories. Enable the file watcher on the root. Write a test file to a subdirectory (not root). Verify the file is detected by the watcher, processed through the transformation pipeline, and output written to the output directory.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Deduplication logic correctly discards duplicate processing requests for the same file path within a configurable time window","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure business logic with no I/O dependencies. The deduplication map and time window are testable through direct function calls with mocked time (Date.now or equivalent). A real failure—e.g., the deduplication key is incorrect, or the time check uses < instead of <=—is caught by Unit tests that verify logic in isolation. No filesystem, subprocess, or external system behavior is involved.","test_description":"Mock the system clock. Call the deduplication check twice with the same file path within the time window; verify the second call is blocked. Advance the clock past the time window and verify the same path is no longer blocked. Test boundary conditions (exactly at window edge, immediately before/after).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.1,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Daemon processes a file exactly once even when the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure occurs at the integration boundary between the filesystem event handler and the deduplication logic. Unit tests of deduplication logic alone (behavior 2) verify that identical paths are deduplicated, but they don't verify that the event handler correctly passes file paths to deduplication, or that multiple rapid filesystem events trigger the deduplication correctly. A real failure (file processed twice) requires wiring these modules together. Integration testing with mocked filesystem events firing in rapid succession for the same file path, or real filesystem writes that trigger multiple OS events, catches the actual failure.","test_description":"Mock fs.watch to emit multiple 'change' events in rapid succession (e.g., within 10ms) for the same file path. Verify the file handler's processing pipeline is invoked exactly once, not multiple times. Verify that queued transformations and output writes happen only once.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without restart","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A real failure occurs when fs.watch()'s behavior on directory deletion/recreation is 